  "prompt": "If any unknown person complaint FIR (not name in FIR) against me then what I should do?",
  "response": "If someone has filed a First Information Report (FIR) against you but you are not named in it, here are some steps you can take:\n\n1. **Stay Calm:** It's important to remain calm and avoid panicking. An FIR does not mean that you are guilty of any crime.\n\n2. **Obtain a Copy of the FIR:** You have the right to request a copy of the FIR from the police station where it was filed. This will help you understand the nature of the complaint.\n\n3. **Consult a Lawyer:** It\u2019s advisable to seek legal counsel. A lawyer can help you understand your rights, the implications of the FIR, and the best course of action.\n\n4. **Do Not Ignore the FIR:** Even if you are not named, it\u2019s important to respond appropriately. Ignoring the FIR could lead to complications later.\n\n5. **Cooperate with Authorities:** If the police contact you for questioning or clarification, cooperate with them. However, it is advisable to have your lawyer present during any questioning.\n\n6. **Document Everything:** Keep a record of all communications related to the FIR, including any correspondence with the police or your lawyer.\n\n7. **Prepare Your Defense:** If necessary, work with your lawyer to prepare a defense or a statement that addresses the allegations made in the FIR.\n\n8. **Do Not Leave the Jurisdiction:** If the FIR is serious, it might be advisable to stay within the jurisdiction until the matter is resolved.\n\n9. **Avoid Discussing the Matter Publicly:** Refrain from discussing the case on social media or with friends, as this could affect your situation.\n\n10. **Consider Legal Recourse:** If you believe the FIR is false or malicious, your lawyer may advise you on the possibility of filing a defamation suit or other legal actions.\n\nEach situation is unique, so the best course of action can vary. Always rely on legal advice tailored to your specific circumstances.",
